(1, 'Sets of Objects And Numbers', 2, '<div class="row" style="margin: 0;">\n        <div class="col-md-3 text-left">\n            \n            <div>\n                <h3>Content</h3>\n                <ul style="list-style: none;margin: 0;padding: 0; font-size:15px">\n                    <li> <u> <a href="#set">Set</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Types-of-Sets">Types of Sets</a></u> </li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Venn-Diagrams">Venn Diagrams</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Subsets">Subsets</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Types-of-Subset">Types of Subset</a></u></li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Sets-Of-Number">Sets Of Number</a></u> </li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Using-Venn-Diagrams-and-Application"> Using Venn Diagrams and Application</a></u> </li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Properties-Of-Set-Operation"> Properties Of Set Operation</a></u> </li>\n                </ul>\n            </div>\n           \n            \n        </div>\n       <div class="col-md-9" >\n           <div class="jumbotron" style="font-size: 100">\n        \n<h2 id="set"><strong>Set of Object and Numbers</strong></h2><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Set</strong> is a well defined collection or list of object, symbols, names, numbers or ideas.&nbsp;</p><p>Ex: Consider the follow collection:</p><ul><li>Months of a year</li><li>Colors of a rainbow.</li><li>Vowels of the English</li><li>Positive integer etc.</li></ul><h3><br>&nbsp;</h3><h3 id="Types-of-Sets"><strong>Types of Sets:</strong></h3><p><strong>Finite Set</strong>: A set whose last member can be found.&nbsp;</p><p><i> <pre>Ex A ={1,2,3,4,5,...10}.</pre> </i></p><p><strong>Infinite Set</strong>: A set whose last member can not be found.&nbsp;</p><p><i> <pre>Ex C = {1,2,3,4,5,…} .</pre> </i></p><p><strong>Unit Set:</strong> A set which has only one member.&nbsp;</p><p><i> <pre>Ex B = {Y}.</pre> </i></p><p><strong>Null or Empty set:</strong> A set which has no member or element.&nbsp;</p><p><i> <pre> Ex A = {}.&nbsp;</pre></i></p><p><i>NOTE: {Ø} is not a null set but rather a set of null element meaning unit set.</i></p><p><strong>Universal Set:</strong> A set of all the objects under discussion.&nbsp;</p><p><i> <pre>Ex A U B = {1,2,3,4,5...10,Y}.</pre> </i></p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Venn-Diagrams"><strong>Venn Diagrams</strong></h3><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/venn diagrams.png" alt="Venn            Diagrams"><figcaption><strong>Venn Diagrams</strong></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Subsets"><strong>Subsets</strong></h3><p><strong>Subsets</strong> is a portion of a set or a set that include other set. Denoted by ϲ. If each element of a set A is also an element of set B, then A is a subset of B or A is contained in B.</p><p>Symbolically: A ϲ B means “A is a subset of B”.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i>NOTE: A subset might have no member(s), in this case it is termed the null set or empty set. The null set is a subset of every set.</i></p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/subset.png" alt="Subsets"><figcaption>A set can be a subset of itself.</figcaption></figure><p><br>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Types-of-Subset"><i><strong>Types of Subset</strong></i></h3><p><strong>Super-set:</strong>&nbsp;</p><p>Is a set that includes other sets. <i>Ex A ϲ B, then A is a subset of B and B is a super-set of A.</i></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Improper Subset:</strong><br>Contains every member of the original set.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/improper.png" alt=""><figcaption>A is contained in B</figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Proper Subset:</strong><br>Does not contain every member of the original set.&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/proper.png" alt=""><figcaption>A is subset of B.</figcaption></figure><h3>&nbsp;</h3><h3>&nbsp;</h3><h3 id="Sets-Of-Number"><strong>Sets Of Number</strong></h3><p>A set of <strong>natural numbers.</strong> {1,2,3,4,5…} and denoted by symbol <i>N.</i></p><p>A set of <strong>whole numbers</strong>. {0,1,2,3,4,5,6,…} and is denoted by symbol <i>W.</i></p><p>A set of <strong>odd numbers</strong>.{1,3,5,7,9,11,…} <i>NOTE: negative too can be odd numbers.</i></p><p>A set of <strong>even numbers </strong><i>{2,4,6,8,10,…}</i>&nbsp;</p><p><i>NOTE: negative too can be even numbers.&nbsp;</i><br>&nbsp;</p><p>A set of <strong>multiples of n</strong>. &nbsp;<i>{n,2n,3n,4n,5n,…}</i></p><p>A set of <strong>integers</strong> is the set of positive and negative whole numbers.&nbsp;<i> {…,-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3,…}&nbsp;</i></p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Using-Venn-Diagrams-and-Application"><strong>Using Venn Diagrams and Application</strong></h3><p><br>&nbsp;</p><h4><i>Intersection of sets</i></h4><p>The set of object which belong to set A and at the same time set B.</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/subsetoperation.png" alt=""><figcaption>The C is the intersection of set A and B. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;B is the intersection of set A. &nbsp;and &nbsp; &nbsp;<i>U is the union of set.</i></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><h4><i>Disjoints sets&nbsp;</i><br>&nbsp;</h4><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/disjoint.png" alt="Disjoints                                                             sets "><figcaption>If no member of A belongs to set B.</figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><h3>&nbsp;</h3><h4><i>Complement Of A Set</i>&nbsp;</h4><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/union.png" alt=""><figcaption>If set A is a subset of the universal set, the Complement of A is the set of members which belong to the universal set U do not belong to A.</figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Properties-Of-Set-Operation"><strong>Properties Of Set Operation</strong></h3><p><strong>Commutative property </strong><a href="/basicLevel?name=Number_And_Numerals&amp;field=Mathemathics&amp;id_feild=1#Properties-of-Operation"><strong>[]</strong></a></p><p><i>Consider set A and B. A ∩B = B ∩A <strong>and</strong> A U B = B U A</i><br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Associative property </strong><a href="/basicLevel?name=Number_And_Numerals&amp;field=Mathemathics&amp;id_feild=1#Properties-of-Operation"><strong>[]</strong></a></p><p><i>Consider set A,B and C. (A ∩B ) ∩ C = A ∩(B ∩ C) <strong>and</strong> (A U B ) U C = A U (B U C)</i></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Distributive property </strong><a href="/basicLevel?name=Number_And_Numerals&amp;field=Mathemathics&amp;id_feild=1#Properties-of-Operation"><strong>[]</strong></a></p><p><i>Consider set A,B and C. A U ( B ∩ C)= (A U B) ∩ (A U C)</i></p>\n\n            \n       </div>\n    </div>\n \n    </div>', '2020-08-31 09:42:58', '2020-08-31 09:42:58'),
(2, ' Number And Numerals', 1, '    <div class="row" style="margin: 0;">\n        <div class="col-md-3 text-left">\n <h3>Content</h3>\n <ul style="list-style: none;margin: 0;padding: 0; font-size:15px">\n     <li> <u> <a href="#Square-Numbers">Square Numbers</a></u></li>\n     <li> <u><a href="#Prime-And-Composite-Numbers">Prime And Composite Numbers</a></u> </li>\n     <li> <u><a href="#Factors">Factors</a></u></li>\n     <li>  <u><a href="#Properties-of-Operation">Properties of Operation</a></u> </li>\n </ul>\n     \n        </div>\n       <div class="col-md-9" >\n           <div class="jumbotron" style="font-size: 100">\n            <h2 id="Square-Numbers"><strong>Square Numbers</strong></h2><p>The square of any number is the number multiplied by itself.</p><p>Ex: The square of 3 is 3x3 = 9.</p><p>The usual notation for the square of a number <i>n</i> is not the product <i>n</i>×<i>n</i>, but the equivalent exponentiation <i>n</i> <sup>2</sup>, usually pronounced as "<i>n</i> squared".</p><p>Ex: 3<sup>2</sup>,2<sup>2</sup>,1<sup>2</sup>, etc.</p><p><i>NOTE: The square of a whole number is called perfect square.</i></p><p><br><strong>Square Root</strong></p><p>In mathematics, a square root of a number x is a number y such that y<sup>2</sup> = x; in other words, a number y whose square (the result of multiplying the number by itself, or y x y) is x.</p><p>The notation for square root n = √x. √ is the symbol for square root.</p><p>Ex: √4 = 2 because 2x2 = 4, √9 = 3 because 3x3 = 9.<br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Square Root of a Rational Number</strong></p><p>To find the square root of a rational number, find the square roots of the numerator and the denominator separately. Ex: √4/9 ,&nbsp;</p><p><i>NOTE 4 is the numerator and 9 is the denominator.</i></p><p>√4/9 = √4/√9 = 2/3<br><br>&nbsp;</p><h2 id="Prime-And-Composite-Numbers"><strong>Prime And Composite Numbers</strong></h2><p><strong>prime numbers</strong> are whole <strong>numbers</strong> greater than 1, that have only two factors – 1 and the <strong>number</strong> itself. <strong>Prime numbers</strong> are divisible only by the <strong>number</strong> 1 or itself. For example, 2, 3, 5, 7 and 11 are the first few <strong>prime numbers</strong>.</p><p><i>NOTE: 1 is not a prime number, and 2 is the only even prime number.</i></p><p>Numbers that have more than 2 factors are called <strong>composite numbers.</strong><br><br>&nbsp;</p><h2 id="Factors"><strong>Factors</strong></h2  ><p>Factors are whole numbers that are multiplied together to produce another number. The original numbers are factors of the product number. Ex: 1 is a factor of every number, and every number is a factor of itself.<br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Common Factors</strong></p><p>When we find the <strong>factors</strong> of two or more numbers, and then find some <strong>factors</strong> are the same ("<strong>common</strong>"), then they are the "<strong>common factors</strong>".</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Prime Factors</strong></p><p>A factor that is a prime number.</p><p>Ex: The factors of 21 are 1,3,7,21. Here 3,7,and 21 are prime and also a factor of 21, hence the prime factor of 21.<br>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Highest Common Factor</strong><br>The <i>highest</i> number that divides exactly into two or more numbers.</p><p>Ex: the common factor of 14,16 factors of 14 is 1,2,7,14 and the factors of 16 are 1,2,4,8,16 the common factors in 14,16 are 1 and 2, hence the highest common factor is the 2.</p><p><strong>Lowest Common Multiple</strong></p><p>The <i>lowest common multiple</i> of two numbers is the smallest whole number which is a multiple of both.</p><p>Ex: Multiples of 2 is 2,4,<strong>6</strong>,8,10,<strong>12</strong>.. and the multiples of 3 is 3,<strong>6</strong>,9,<strong>12</strong>,15… common multiples of 6 and 12 hence the lowest common multiple is <strong>6</strong><br>&nbsp;</p><h2  id="Properties-of-Operation"><strong>Properties of Operation</strong></h2><p><strong>Closure</strong></p><p>When all answers fall into the original set. If you add two even numbers, the answer is still an even number (4 + 6 = 10); therefore, the set of even numbers <i>is<strong> closed</strong></i><strong> under addition.</strong></p><p>If you add two odd numbers, the answer is not an odd number (3 + 9 = 12); therefore, the set of odd numbers is <i>not closed</i> under addition.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Commutative</strong></p><p>The <i>order</i> does not make any difference in the result.&nbsp;</p><p>Given any two rational numbers a and b:&nbsp;</p><p>a + b = b + a we say <i>addition</i> of rational number is <strong>commutative</strong> under <i>addition</i>. <pre>Ex: 2+3 = 3+2 = 5</pre> </p><p>a - b ≠ b - a we say <i>subtraction</i> of rational number is <strong>not commutative</strong> under <i>subtraction</i>. <pre>Ex: 2-3 ≠ 3-2</pre> </p><p>a x b = b x a we say <i>multiplication</i> of rational number is <strong>commutative</strong> under <i>multiplication</i>.<pre>Ex: 2x3 = 3x2 = 6</pre>  </p><p>a / b ≠ b / a we say <i>division</i> of rational number is <strong>not commutative</strong> under <i>division</i>.<pre> Ex: 2/3 ≠ 3/2</pre></p><p><strong>Associative Property</strong></p><p>Given any three rational a,b and c.&nbsp;</p><p>a + (b + c) = (a + b) + c we say <i>addition</i> of rational number is <strong>Associative</strong> under <i>addition</i>. <br> <pre>Ex: 1+(2+3) = (3+2) + 1 = 6</pre> </p><p>a - (b - c) ≠ (a - b) - c we say <i>addition</i> of rational number is <strong>not</strong> <strong>Associative</strong> under <i>subtraction</i>.  <br> <pre>Ex: 3-(2-1) ≠ (3-2) – 1</pre> </p><p>a x (b x c) = (a x b) x c we say <i>multiplication</i> of rational number is <strong>Associative</strong> under <i>multiplication</i>. <br><pre>Ex: 2x(2x3) = (3x2) x 2 = 12</pre>  </p><p> <pre></pre> a / (b / c) ≠ (a / b) / c we say <i>divisions</i> of rational number is <strong>not</strong> <strong>Associative</strong> under <i>divisions</i>. <br> <pre>Ex: 3/(2/1) ≠ (3/2) /1</pre> </p><p><strong>Distributive Property</strong></p><p>Given any three rational numbers a,b and c. a(b+c) = ab + ac means multiplication (x) is distributive over addition (+).&nbsp;</p><p>  <pre>Ex: 3(4 + 5) = (3 x 4) + (3 x 5)</pre>  .</p>   \n           </div>\n       </div>\n    </div>', '2020-08-31 04:00:00', NULL),
(3, 'Fractions', 3, '\n    <div class="row" style="margin: 0;">\n        <div class="col-md-3 text-left">\n            \n            <div>\n                <h3>Content</h3>\n                <ul style="list-style: none;margin: 0;padding: 0; font-size:15px">\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Fractions">Fractions</a></u> </li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Types-of-fraction">Types of fraction</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Chat-Presentation-of-Fraction.">Chat Presentation of Fraction.</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Equivalent-Fractions.">Equivalent Fractions.</a></u></li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Simplest-form-Fractions.">Simplest form Fractions.</a></u> </li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Comparing-Fractions."> Comparing Fractions.</a></u> </li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Changing-Mixed-Fraction.">Changing\n                      Mixed Fraction.</a></u> </li>\n                      <li>  <u><a href="#Changing-into-Mixed-Fraction.">Changing\n                        into Mixed Fraction.</a></u> </li>\n                        \n                        <li>  <u><a href="#Addition-and-subtraction-of-Fraction.">Addition\n                          and subtraction of Fraction.</a></u> </li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Multiplication-of-Fraction.">Multiplication\n                      of Fraction.</a></u> </li>\n                      <li>  <u><a href="#Division-Of-Fraction.">Division\n                        Of Fraction.</a></u> </li>\n                </ul>\n            </div>\n           \n            \n        </div>\n       <div class="col-md-9" >\n           <div class="jumbotron" style="font-size: 100">\n\n            <font face="Liberation Serif, serif"> <h2 id="Fractions">Fractions </h2>  </font></p>\n            <p  style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%">\n              A fraction represents a part of a whole or, more generally, any number of equal parts.\n            </p>\n            <br>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"> <h3 id="Types-of-fraction"> Types\n              of fraction:</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Common\n            Fractions: 	Numbers like ½ , ¾, etc. One number over the other.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Decimal\n            Fraction:	Numbers like 0.75,0.2,etc. Numbers with decimals.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Percentages\n            Fraction: Numbers like 85%,70%,10%,etc. Numbers with percentage\n            symbol(%).</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Common\n             Fractions.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Forms\n            of Common Fraction.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Proper\n            Fractions:	A fraction is said to be a proper fraction if the\n            numerator is less than the denominator. </font>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n             ½ , ¾, etc.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Improper\n            Fractions:	A fraction is said to be improper fraction if the\n            numerator is greater than the denominator.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            11/6, 7/2, 5/3, etc.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Mixed\n            Fractions: 	A fraction is said to be mixed fraction if both whole\n            number and rational numbers are part of the fraction.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_d24b2f8196d67edf.gif" name="Object1" hspace="8" width="74" height="38"/>\n            ,\n            etc</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"> \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Like\n            Fractions:	If two or more fractions are said to have the same\n            denominator.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            ¼, ¾  the have the same denominator of 4 hence like fraction.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n              \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Unlike\n            Fractions:	If two or more fractions are said to have the same\n            denominator.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            1/3, 4/5, the have different number of denominator, hence unlike\n            fraction.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Chat-Presentation-of-Fraction.">Chat Presentation of Fraction.</h3></font></p>\n            <br>\n            <div class="row">\n              <div class="col-4">\n                <img src="/basicimage/3x3.png" height="170px" name="Shape3" alt="Shape3" />\n                <i class="text-center">3/6</i>\n                \n              </div>\n              <div class="col-4">\n                <img src="/basicimage/2x4.png" height="170px" name="Shape3_0" alt="Shape3_0" />\n                <i class="text-center">2/6</i>\n              </div>\n              <div class="col-4">\n                <img src="/basicimage/1x5.png" height="170px" name="Shape3_1" alt="Shape3_1" />\n                <i class="text-center">1/6</i>\n              </div>\n            </div>\n           \n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 150%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Equivalent-Fractions.">Equivalent Fractions.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 150%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Two\n            or more fractions are said to be equivalent if the numerator and the\n            denominator are from the same multiplier.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n             2/5, 6/15 and 12/30  are said to be equivalent fractions since they\n            are from the same smaller fraction 2/5,  6/15 is formed by\n            multiplying both the numerator and the denominator by 3 and 12/30 is\n            form by multiplying both the numerator and the denominator by 6.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Simplest-form-Fractions.">Simplest form Fractions.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">The\n            cancellation of common fraction is the simplifying of fraction.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n             \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_35f136cdd5b327b9.gif" name="Object2" hspace="8" width="174" height="42"/>\n            and\n            2/3 is the simplest form of 12/30</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Comparing-Fractions.">Comparing Fractions.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Fractions\n            can be compare by using symbols &lt; or &gt;. where  &lt; means a\n            number is less than the other and &gt; means a number is greater than\n            the other.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n              2&lt; 4 means 2 is less than 4 and 4 &gt; 2 means 4 is greater than\n            2.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"> \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">NOTE:\n            4 &gt; 2 can also mean  2 is less than 4 and 2 &lt; 4 can also mean 4\n            greater than 2. Don’t look the symbols look at how it works.   </font>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">In\n            fraction comparison.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">You\n            first check the size of the denominator, if the size is </font><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">larger</font><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">\n            than the numerator then the result is less than (1) and check the\n            numerator if it too small the the result is close to (0).</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 150%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            Comparing  \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_cc9b9a36902e3f03.gif" name="Object3" hspace="8" width="58" height="38"/>\n            </font><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">\n            </font><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Here, ¾ has the\n            denominator larger than the numerator hence the size is less than 1.\n            5/3 has the denominator less than the numerator hence the size is\n            greater than 1.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 150%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">and\n            7/2 has the denominator less than the numerator hence the size is\n            greater than 1. Now we know that ¾ is the least fraction. Let check\n            the 5/3 and 7/2. 5/3 the numerator is not too that large than 3,</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 150%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">just\n            (5 – 3 = 2) (2) difference and the result is said to be in-between\n            (1 and 2) . 7/2 has (7-2 = 5) (5) difference which is twice the\n            denominator, hence the result is said to be in-between (3  and 4).</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 150%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">t</font><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">here, for\n            7/2 is larger than 5/3 .  Arrangement  \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_131fca0bd0ada229.gif" name="Object4" hspace="8" width="65" height="38"/>\n            </font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Changing-Mixed-Fraction.">Changing\n              Mixed Fraction.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n             \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_f6985b8f7939f722.gif" name="Object5" hspace="8" width="152" height="39"/>\n            \n            Explanation, you multiple the whole number by the denominator and add\n            it to the numerator and divide the result by the numerator.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex2:\n              <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_95f17335dc17495d.gif" name="Object6" hspace="8" width="139" height="39"/>\n            </font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Changing-into-Mixed-Fraction.">Changing\n              into Mixed Fraction.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_6936ba4f981aaee0.gif" name="Object7" hspace="8" width="61" height="38"/>\n            <font face="Liberation Serif, serif">explanation\n            5 goes into 12 (2) times and the remainder is (2). And you divide the\n            remainder by 5.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Addition\n            and Subtraction of Fractions.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Fractions\n            can only me add or subtracted if they have the same denominator.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Addition-and subtraction-of-Fraction.">Addition\n              and subtraction of Fraction.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Simplify\n            the fraction and make sure the fractions have equal denominator.\n            Adding mixed fraction make sure you have converted it to proper or\n            improper fraction and the denominator is the same.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_c4632247ffdded1b.gif" name="Object9" hspace="8" width="114" height="38"/>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_62823c66f2a1403b.gif" name="Object8" hspace="8" width="245" height="42"/>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">							</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_e971860faf7be7e0.gif" name="Object10" hspace="8" width="340" height="38"/>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Multiplication-of-Fraction.">Multiplication\n              of Fraction.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">To\n            multiply two fraction you multiple the numerator and the denominator.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n             \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_c24c3ae7c9a3b28f.gif" name="Object11" hspace="8" width="113" height="38"/>\n            </font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_ab9708b24b7337e1.gif" name="Object12" hspace="8" width="218" height="42"/>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_c4bef3f442ac4ae3.gif" name="Object13" hspace="8" width="285" height="38"/>\n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif"><h3 id="Division-Of-Fraction.">Division\n              Of Fraction.</h3></font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">To\n            division of fraction involves  two rules.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">1.\n            To divide a whole number by a fraction, multiply that whole number by\n            the reciprocal of the fraction.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">2.\n            To divide a fraction by a whole number, multiple the fraction by the\n            inverse of the whole number.</font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            rule 1,    \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_38afdaf21d41e7a6.gif" name="Object14" hspace="8" width="285" height="42"/>\n            </font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><font face="Liberation Serif, serif">Ex:\n            rule 2, \n            <img src="/basicimage/Fractions_html_7ffcb04b07087cc0.gif" name="Object15" hspace="8" width="200" height="38"/>\n            </font></p>\n            <p style="margin-bottom: 0in; line-height: 100%"><br/>\n            \n            </p>\n\n            \n       </div>\n    </div>\n \n    </div>', '2020-09-04 04:00:00', NULL),
(4, 'SHAPE AND SPACE', 4, ' <div class="row" style="margin: 0;">\n        <div class="col-md-3 text-left">\n            \n            <div>\n                <h3>Content</h3>\n                <ul style="list-style: none;margin: 0;padding: 0; font-size:15px">\n                    <li> <u><a href="#SHAPE-AND-SPACE">SHAPE AND SPACE</a></u> </li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Solid-Figures">Solid Figures</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Cuboid">Cuboid</a></u></li>\n                    <li> <u><a href="#Prism">Prism</a></u></li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Pyramid">Pyramid</a></u> </li>\n                    <li>  <u><a href="#Net">Net </a></u> </li>\n                   \n                </ul>\n            </div>\n           \n            \n        </div>\n       <div class="col-md-9" >\n           <div class="jumbotron" style="font-size: 100">\n<h2 id="SHAPE-AND-SPACE" ><strong>SHAPE AND SPACE</strong></h2><p><strong>Shape</strong> is the appearance of something in terms of its arrangements in <i>space</i>, especially its outline.</p><p><strong>Space</strong> is distance between or physical extent across two or three dimensions; area, volume.</p><p><br><strong>Line Segment</strong>: is a part of a straight line bounded by two point. Let A and B be two point on a line.</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/lingsegment.png" alt="lingsegment"><figcaption><strong>Line Segment</strong></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Ray</strong>: is a ling segment where one end of the line is extended endlessly.</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/ray.png" alt="lingsegment"><figcaption><strong>Ray</strong></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Vertex</strong>: Is the point where two or move lines connect to form a corner.</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/vertex.png" alt="lingsegment"><figcaption>There are four vertices, The vertex at A,B,C and D.</figcaption></figure><p><br>&nbsp;</p><p><i>Note the joint at the middle are not vertex, vertex makes a corner.</i></p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Solid-Figures"><strong>Solid Figures</strong></h3><p><strong>Solid figures</strong> have faces,Vertex and edges.</p><p>Ex:Cuboid, Prisms, Pyramid etc.</p><h3 id="Cuboid"><strong>Cuboid</strong></h3><p>A <strong>cuboid</strong> is a box-shape object, it has six flat sides and all angles adjacent between sides are right angles and of its faces are rectangles.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/cuboid.png" alt="lingsegment"><figcaption><i>It has 6 faces, 12 edges and 8 vertices.</i></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Edge</strong> is a line segment joining two adjacent vertices.</p><p><strong>Face</strong> is the flat bounding surfaces of a solid figure.</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Prism"><strong>Prism</strong></h3><p>A <strong>prism</strong> is a 3-dimensional <strong>shape</strong> with two identical <strong>shapes</strong> facing each other.</p><p>Ex: Rectangular Prism, Pentagonal Prism, Cylinder,etc</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/prism.png"><figcaption><i>3 faces, 2 edges and 0 vertex &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 6 faces, 12 edges and 8 vertices</i></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Pyramid"><strong>Pyramid</strong></h3><p>A <strong>pyramid</strong> is a structure whose outer surfaces are triangular and converge to a single step at the top, making the shape roughly a pyramid in the geometric sense.</p><p>Ex: Rectangular Pyramid, Triangular Pyramid, etc.</p><p><br>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/pyramid.png"><figcaption><i>5 faces, 8 edges and 5 vertex &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 4 faces, 6 edges and 4 vertex</i></figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><h3 id="Net"><strong>Net&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>Net is the flat representation of a solid figure that can be folded to make the figure it represent.</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/net.png"><figcaption>Cube Net</figcaption></figure><p>&nbsp;</p><figure class="image"><img src="/basicimage/pyramid2.png"><figcaption>Square Pyramid Net</figcaption></figure>\n       </div>\n    </div>\n \n    </div>', '2020-09-09 04:00:00', NULL);

